Save these core drills the next time you want to REALLY challenge your core 🔥 also lol at @bennettandrewjordan when he’s surprised my core is crazy strong 💪🏼 

1️⃣ STRADDLE LIFT : modify by keeping one or both legs on the floor. 5 rounds 

2️⃣ V UP- modify with one leg at a time. 5x

3️⃣ Boat to lift - modify keeping toes on the floor in the lift 5x

Key here is engaging mula bandha (pelvic floor!) This is the key to a lot of refined muscular engagement- athletes regularly use it without thinking. Try to lift all sides evenly.

These movements improve functional core strength, hip flexors, “push” strength (builds toward handstands) and compression strength (for press/ floats.)

Any q’s lemme know below! Also know you can train with me at anytime @joinlila 

#yoga #yogacore #yogacoredrills @yoga @yogapractice

How to stay motivated to work out, the easy way 🤍

👉🏼 Stop thinking it’s about motivation or discipline, decision fatigue is real, and we should use that higher order thinking for our work/ creative pursuits

Instead, make your movement
👉🏼ENJOYABLE, something you think is fun and feels good in the moment.
👉🏼daily 20min. High frequency is the key to see results

Save this! 📚 MOBILITY is essential for life long healthy joints, injury prevention, muscle soreness, movement freedom & more. Pair that with the controlled breathing & non-judgmental awareness of yoga & you’ve got my current favorite routine 🤍

Movements I’d recommend:

FULL BODY MOBILITY 🤍 

— 90/90. I’ve swapped out pigeon for this more active stretch that targets the same muscle groups (deep glutes/ rotators)

-yogi squat/ low squat/ full squat. essential for ankle, knee and hip mobility. one of the primary movements of the body. use or it lose it!

-cossack squat/ skandasana/ side squat. focuses on the single leg mobility and provides more adductor/ inner thigh work

-good mornings. this is a complete new one I picked up! basically a yogi squat to half lift forward fold. really great at getting your hamstrings strong and active and helps prevent yoga butt strains.

-pancake/ straddle - make it active by holding hands behind head

-spinal waves - for interception or body awareness. and spinal segmentation / intelligence. “you are only as young as your spine”

-cat cow. mobility 101. start here.

-cactus. goal post arms. can do in a compound movement like lunge or against the wall. great for getting your shoulders/ neck back in alignment 

-wheel. foundational spinal/ shoulder mobility. 

-dead hangs. new one. decompresses your lower back. builds hand and shoulder strength.

-spinal twists. use it or lose on the rotational axis.

-lunge. foundational for hip flexors/ glutes.

Will do subsequent posts at these 🤍

Yes, yoga will make you stronger, more flexible & balanced, less stressed/ anxious/depressed, and boost your nervous/immune/ lymph/ endocrine systems…

But really the peace of mind & quiet while you practice 🤌 chefs kiss 😚

Yoga teacher goes to the gym! Save this if ALL you do is yoga. 📚I was guilty of this for almost a decade 😅 but noticed lower back pain and unstable joints. I finally got over my resistance to doing other workouts and started my current routine, optimized for HEALTH/ overall longevity:

1. Cardio (we need 180min of zone 2 cardio per week) for optimal heart health. I learned this from @drandygalpin 

 2. Strength training. I like working on progressions for sissy, pistol, shrimp, & dragon squats +  pull ups. The squats are necessary bc my legs are stronger than a regular deep squat and I would either need to add weight OR work on skilled squats like a one legged squat (pistol squat.) I work on pull ups, chin ups, and hangs because there is almost zero pull motion in yoga. @hybrid.calisthenics has great progressions 

I don’t do push ups, leg raises, bridges or twists because those are part of my yoga practice 🙏

I can go more in depth, because I love a science backed routine! But this is working for me now :) let me know if this is useful to you 🫶

I could probably make this a whole dang series! There are so many things I’ve seen over the last 10 years as a yoga instructor that just don’t make sense in *most * people’s bodies. I’ll do a quick take on each one 👇 

1. Twists “detox” your body- no. Your liver does all the detoxing, twists are great for compression in your spine but it’s just scientifically false.

2. “Wring out your organs” - same as before. Perhaps metaphorically? But certainly not literally

3. “Earn your birthday cake!” - Diet culture is so pervasive. Yoga should be a safe space, not one that encourages exercise to look a certain way.

4. “Do this! If you can’t, do this” - I prefer to teach in the positive. Try “ try this if it feels better” 

5. Straight legs in down dog- No brainer. I’ve seen too many hamstring injuries due to this. 

6. Feet together in forward fold- again, too aggressive on hammies.

7. Big toes together, heels apart- Literally no reason to do this. Just stand hips under pelvis. It’s more stable 

8. Straight leg forward fold- too aggressive on hammies 

9. Lotus pose- unnecessary strain on knees. Not for general classes. Just from bone structure many people will not be able to do this. 

10. Scorpion pose- most people aren’t ready for this, it’s a contortion pose and best taught in that setting

11. Relaxed glutes in backbends- Have always known this to be terrible advice. Protect your back! Squeeze your glutes 

12. Shoulders down in downward dog- Not correct anatomical position.

13. Lifted pelvic floor the entire class- Many people have extremely tight & weak pelvic floor. You need to teach both relaxation AND contraction. Not just contraction.

I have so many of these! And have personally suffered injuries from these yoga misconceptions 🥲 let’s do better in 2023! Is there anything you no longer do? Lmk in the comments 🤍

#yoga #yogapractice #yogateacher #yogamyths  #yogateachertraining #yogajourney

As I unrolled my yoga mat for the first time, I was skeptical about what yoga could do for me. The first couple times I tried it, I was in ballet school and yoga was the kind of boring alternative to Pilates class 😅

Rumi once said, ‘Respond to every call that excites your spirit,’ and yoga was calling me in a way that I couldn’t ignore 🤍

Through my practice, I’ve learned that yoga isn’t just about the physical poses, but about the mental and emotional transformations that occur when you’re fully present in your body. It’s taught me to let go of the past, quiet the inner critic, and trust in my own strength and resilience 🙏

Yoga has become my daily reminder to slow down, breathe deeply, and find peace within myself. As I step off my mat, I carry that sense of calm and clarity with me into the rest of my day, and I know that I’m better equipped to handle whatever challenges come my way 🤝

I know a lot of you suffer low back pain too (apparently 80% of the population experiences it!) but luckily yoga does help 🙏

✔️ DO remember that pain is felt in the lower back, but often comes as a result of imbalances or issues from other areas of the body

✔️ DO stretch and strengthen your hip flexors, glutes, and upper back

❌ DON’T only stretch passively (relaxing into a stretch.) Activate your muscles while you practice

✔️ DO start gently and be patient with yourself. You are likely retraining movement patterns 

❌ Don’t push too hard or ignore pain signals. Always prioritize your form over speed, rep or weight

✔️ DO practice spinal segmentation and spinal awareness so that you develop more dexterity and intelligence in the spine

❌ Don’t wear heels if it’s killing your back!

✔️ Do practice movement snacks, or mini yoga sessions, to keep your spine supple all day long 

Hope these help & I have full lower back pain relief videos on my app @joinlila 🤍

I’ve loved yoga for a decade but only recently added functional movement patterns & mobility into my practice & it’s made a HUGE difference. Yoga alone can be too passive 👇🏼

🎓Time for school: Our mobility decreases by about 10% every decade, starting in your 20’s. It may sneak up on you all at once, like one day you could easily touch your toes or reach down to grab something off the floor, and the next your whole body is creaking on the way down 🥲

BUT! You can do something to help prevent that onset! It’s super simple. Your mobility responds to “use it or lose it”. Like a well oiled machine, joints that are pressed and used in their end range can maintain AND improve their resting muscle length ☺️

Luckily yoga has been shown to improve mobility and ROM, and if you add a few motions from the rehab/prehab world to your yoga practice, you’ll create an amazing habit that helps you feel good and your joints happy all your life.

The first part of a daily mobility routine for health & longevity is a FULL SQUAT or Yogi Squat. Add a few thoracic rotations like i’m doing to help target the upper body as well.

The squat is 1 of 6 FOUNDATIONAL movement patterns for humans. Practicing it just a little everyday will do wonders for your ankles, knees & hips (and may help low back pain) and is a wonderful form of active mobility. 

❌Rather than sitting and collapsing into your flexibility, ✔️keeping your muscles active works with your neurology to facilitate greater mobility, strength, control, and stability in your joints leading to better athletic performance while reducing the risk of injury.

So yogis, YES practice yin and feel good flows, but don’t forget to add end range squats 🤍

For full mobility routines, practice with me online 🤍 by DM’ing me MOBILITY

How to help your partner slow down & relax ✨ yoga teacher edition! Holding someone with love and attention does wonders for BOTH of your nervous’ system. Whether it’s your S/O or a friend you know is stressed, a little savasana assist is heavenly 😇 @bennettandrewjordan shows his love through cooking, organizing dates & planning adventures. I’m a touchy person and like to give little massages like these 🤍

1️⃣ Start by having your partner get comfortable lying down. They may like pillows underneath their knees, or a blanket. Have them slow down their breath. 

2️⃣ Rub your hands together with a a few drops of lavender + carrrier oil and hover them over their nose so they get a little aroma therapy and are alerted of your presence

3️⃣ Start by creating space in their neck by gently cupping the back of the head, twisting right and left then placing it back down

4️⃣ Press the palm of your hands into their pecs and shoulders, using your body weight and a gentle lead forward to apply pressure 

5️⃣ Massage their jaw muscles and temples in circular motions

6️⃣ Close the practice by placing your thumbs on their crown and gently lift your hands. 

Don’t be afraid to ask for feedback! And it should feel just as good for you as it did for the recipient. 🤍

4 Ways I Use Yoga to Build Inner Strength 💪🏼🤍
👉🏼To me inner strength is a calm, stable inner core that knows my worth and value no matter what is happening outside me. Whether I win or lose, go up or down, am liked or not, I have this inner piece of myself that is always wholey mine. Here are 4 ways I build it up with yoga 👇🏼

👉🏼Yoga builds confidence.
Whether I’m holding a handstand or see myself able to do things I never dreamed of, each new transition, each little accomplishment helps me build a stronger connection with myself and my feeling that I can handle any challenge that comes my way. It’s an almost visceral confidence in my strength, resilience, and freedom to express myself.

👉🏼Yoga helps process emotions
When we practice yoga, we become more aware of all the little physical sensations, thoughts, and emotions that come up during practice. Off the mat that means I can tune more easily into my inner experience, and when I feel uncomfortable or fearful, I can feel it in my body and name it. That process of not just clamping down on negative experience, but processing and letting it go, builds emotional resiliency. Sometimes I even discover stored or trapped emotional tension in my body, and by physically releasing it, I also emotionally let go.

👉🏼Yoga helps me be less reactive, more kind
When I practice yoga, I learn to observe my thoughts and emotions without judgment or reactivity. This can help me become more self-aware and less reactive in my daily life. By learning to pause before acting on a big emotion, I create just enough space to disengage and walk away… then come back when my head is cool. 

👉🏼Yoga connects you to your intuition
When I practice yoga, I learn to quiet my mind and listen to my inner voice. This inner voice is NOT the loudest, but it ALWAYS has an opinion about where I’m going and what I’m doing. Yoga helps me slow down enough to listen and find clarity.

The truth is that the asanas, or physical practice, is just an excuse to discover everything that’s happening inside 🤍

Yoga, Taoism, and Stoicism all emphasize non attachment 🍂 because non-attachment leads to inner peace and stability… and inner stability leads to being present and making the most of where you are … and making the most out of where you are leads to you (ironically) manifesting the essence of your desire 🤍

Yoga 👉🏼 letting go of attachments to the physical body and the ego, in order to achieve a state of oneness with the universe

Taosim 👉🏼 Wu Wei, or “non-doing,” the best way to achieve our goals is to let go of our attachment to them and allow things to unfold naturally

Stoicism 👉🏼 focus on what you CAN control. Your reason, virtue, and self-control. Let go of things outside of your control and accept the impermanence of materiality

Many paths up the same mountain 🤍 
If you really want something, let it go

How yoga works from a yoga teacher trainer 😌 (save this for later! 📚)

1️⃣💪🏼 Yoga poses- asanas: work your muscles, joints, and connective tissues to increase strength, mobility and balance. It’s is a low impact, full body movement practice at its most basic level.

2️⃣ 🧘‍♀️ Breath control- pranayama: helps you become aware of your breath & how to regulate it. This can increase your lung capacity, oxygen intake, mental clarity and relaxation response.

3️⃣ 🧠 Mindfulness: Practicing yoga increases your mind-body connection by helping you become more aware of your sensations, thoughts, and emotions. Mindfulness can lead to improved self-awareness, emotional regulation, and overall well-being 🫶🏼

4️⃣ 🩹 Resilience: Research suggests that practicing yoga can improve pain tolerance and resilience. A study published in the journal Cerebral Cortex found that regular yoga practice was associated with increased gray matter volume in brain regions involved in pain regulation, emotional processing, and self-awareness. This suggests that yoga may help individuals better tolerate physical and emotional discomfort, and develop greater resilience in the face of stress and adversity. See @hubermanlab ep #76

5️⃣😌 Mental Health: Yoga is a powerful tool for reducing stress and promoting relaxation. Studies have shown that practicing yoga can lower cortisol levels (a hormone associated with stress), reduce anxiety and depression symptoms, and improve overall well-being.

6️⃣🧘 Letting Go: Trauma can be stored in the body as tension, pain, and emotional patterns. Yoga can help you become mindful of your body’s sensations and feelings, allowing you to identify and release tension and emotions that may be held in the body. That may have happened to you if you felt emotional release happens in poses like pigeon or backbends.

When strength meets flexibility 🤝 zombie press handstand! A good yoga practice builds the 3 things required for a zombie press:
- Compression strength - we practice this with boat pose and other V form core work (crunches do not work)
- Upper body strength and mobility- strength in poses like chaturanga and mobility in poses like downward dog
- Balance - This is an insane balance practice, especially in your fingers. As you work your headstands and forearm stands you’ll build body awareness and overall upside down balance. As you work arm balances like crow you’ll build fingertip strength and balance.

The nice thing about yoga is that you don’t just train for the goal. Peak poses like this are kind of like nice side effects of a well rounded, disciplined practice ☺️ By relinquishing attachment to the outcome, all is coming!

The world you live in is a reflection of your own mind. If you see beauty everywhere, you have a beautiful mind 🌺

A small example of this phenomenon happened to me the other day: my friend showed me his orange Subaru and I thought it was the MOST fitting car for him! 🍊

Before that day Id never seen an orange Subaru. Then within 24 hours, I saw 3 more orange Subarus. 🍊🍊🍊

The things that are top of mind for us appear. That’s why gratitude journaling is so important- when we start making lists of all the things we love, all the things we’re grateful for, those very same things appear before us and we have a train of positive momentum going.✨

Just as easy it is for you to downward spiral- a bad thing happens, then you see more and more bad- an upward cycle can just as easily happen, one good thing turns into the next and next (stairway to heaven 😇)

Skeptics would say there is simply objective reality- but I would respond, don’t be so naive. You might have 3 witnesses to a scene and every single witness has a different recollection of what happened, all of them true.

You have a 👏CHOICE 👏in how you see the world. The way you choose is by being deliberate about what you pay attention to. In yoga there is a saying, “where attention goes, life force (prana) flows”. 

Choose to see the good, the beauty, the harmony… and go to places that make it easy for you to do that 🤍

“Life is a mirror. Smile at it and it smiles back at you”

In this study, researchers compared North American yogis (of various styles) to individually matched controls using sensory testing and MRI techniques. 🧠

👉🏼The yogis had been practicing for an average of 10 years and practiced at least 9 hours a week. Controls were matched in terms of age, sex, education level, and BMI.

🔥Sensory testing involved applying a painful heat stimulus to the forearm and measuring the participants pain tolerance via MRI.

🙏The researchers found that the yogis had 2x more pain tolerance than controls. 
🙏Yogis had more grey matter in multiple brain regions, including the insular cortex
🙏 Yogis had increased left intrainsular white matter integrity 
🙏 Researchers concluded that regular and long-term yoga practice improves pain tolerance by changing the structure and function of the insular cortex, that can lead to changes in the way the brain processes pain signals.

✨✨ This is one of the unique benefits of yoga, different from other forms of physical exercise like stretching or calisthenics. Yes, you may get strong and mobile with yoga, but do NOT forget that mindfulness is a trained skill and has measurable effects on the brain✨✨

PMID: 23696725
